The Number of Political Parties

We might think that the party system in the U.S. doesnt offer enough variety.

We might think our democracy would improve if we simply had more parties.

Question

Why dont we have more parties?

Question

How many parties do we have in the United States?

2014 House of Representatives Election Results

2014 House of Commons Election Results

Question

How can we measure the number of political parties?

Effective Number of Electoral Parties

\(ENEP = \frac{1}{\sum_{i = 1}^n p_i^2}\), where \(n\) is the total number of parties that received votes and \(p_i\) represents the vote share for party \(i\).

Question

How can we measure the proportionality of the electoral rules?

Load Data

# load data
cg <- read.csv("data/clark-golder-2006.csv")

Plot Data

plot(cg$average_magnitude, cg$enep)

Fit Linear Model with Least Squares

m <- lm(enep ~ average_magnitude, data = cg)
coef(m)
##       (Intercept) average_magnitude 
##       3.968080326       0.009803759

Add Line to Plot

plot(cg$average_magnitude, cg$enep)
abline(m)

Our Model

\(y = \alpha + \beta x + \epsilon\)

\(\text{ENEP} = \alpha + \beta \text{magnitude} + \epsilon\)

\(\text{ENEP} = 3.97 + 0.01 \text{magnitude} + \epsilon\)

\(\text{mean}(\text{ENEP} | \text{magnitude}) = 3.97 + 0.01 \text{magnitude}~ \leftarrow\) conditional mean

Assuming this model is correct, what can we say about it? How can we intepret it?

Question

What is this a line of?

\(mean(y)\) versus \(mean(y | x)\)

Question

What does our model say about single-member districts?

Model, what do you say about single-member districts?

\begin{align} \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude}) &= 3.97 + 0.01 \text{magnitude}\\ \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude} = 1) &= 3.97 + 0.01 \times 1\\ \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude} = 1) &= 3.97 + 0.01\\ \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude} = 1) &= 3.98 \end{align}

Question

What does our model say about ten-member districts?

Model, what do you say about ten-member districts?

\begin{align} \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude}) &= 3.97 + 0.01 \text{magnitude}\\ \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude} = 10) &= 3.97 + 0.01 \times 10\\ \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude} = 10) &= 3.97 + 0.1\\ \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude} = 10) &= 4.07 \end{align}

Question

What does our model say about 100-member districts?

Model, what do you say about 100-member districts?

\begin{align} \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude}) &= 3.97 + 0.01 \text{magnitude}\\ \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude} = 100) &= 3.97 + 0.01 \times 100\\ \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude} = 100) &= 3.97 + 1.0\\ \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude} = 100) &= 4.97 \end{align}

These are called predicted values.

Question

So how can we interpret a linear regression model?

  1. We can calculate predicted values.

Question

But what would happen if we switched from single-member districts to 100-member districts?

\begin{align} \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude} = 100) - \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude} = 1) &\\ 4.97 - 3.97 &= 1.00 \end{align}

Wed gain about one party, on average.

Question

But what would happen if we switched from single-member districts to 10-member districts?

\begin{align} \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude} = 10) - \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude} = 1) & \\ 4.07 - 3.97 &= 0.010 \end{align}

Wed gain about one-tenth of a party, on average.

These are called first differences.

Question

So how can we interpret a linear regression model?

  1. We can calculate predicted values.
  2. We can caluclate first differences.

Question

What if we increased magnitude by 1?

\begin{align} \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude} = a + 1) &- \text{mean}(\text{ENEP}~|~\text{magnitude} = a)\\ 3.97 + 0.01 \times (a + 1) & - [3.97 + 0.01 \times a]\\ 3.97 + 0.01 \times a + 0.01 \times 1 & - [3.97 + 0.01 \times a] \\ 3.97 + 0.01 \times a & - [3.97 + 0.01 \times a] + 0.01 \\ (3.97 + 0.01 \times a) & - (3.97 + 0.01 \times a) + 0.01 = 0.1 \leftarrow \text{look familiar?} \end{align}

In general, we can say that a one unit increase in \(x\) leads to a \(\beta\) unit increase in the mean of \(y\).

Question

So how can we interpret a linear regression model?

  1. We can calculate predicted values.
  2. We can caluclate first differences.
  3. We can look at the slope.

Question

Which is more informative?

# correlation 
cor(cg$average_magnitude, cg$enep)
## [1] 0.1497798
# linear regression
coef(m)
##       (Intercept) average_magnitude 
##       3.968080326       0.009803759

In R

# predicted values
coef(m)[1] + coef(m)[2]*1
coef(m)[1] + coef(m)[2]*10
coef(m)[1] + coef(m)[2]*100

# first differences
coef(m)[1] + coef(m)[2]*10 - coef(m)[1] + coef(m)[2]*1
coef(m)[1] + coef(m)[2]*100 - coef(m)[1] + coef(m)[2]*1

# alternative way to calculate first differences
coef(m)[2]*10 - coef(m)[2]*1
coef(m)[2]*100 - coef(m)[2]*1

# slope
coef(m)[2]
